# Business Logic — Cost Model

> Read this file completely before touching any code that involves costs, rates,
> allocations, or EOTP. Getting this wrong produces incorrect billing data.

---

## Resource Types

Every resource belongs to one of three types. The type determines the entire cost calculation.

| Type | Cost Formula |
|---|---|
| `INTERNAL` | `quantity × nbrDaysPerYear × effective_rate` (FTE path) **OR** `manDays × effective_rate` (man-days path) |
| `EXTERNAL` | Same formulas as INTERNAL — different (higher) rates |
| `DIRECT_COST` | `quantity × Rate.dailyRate` — unit model, not man-days |

---

## manDays vs. quantity — Precedence

- If `manDays > 0`, it takes **precedence** over `quantity` for both cost and FTE calculations.
- In practice the two fields are mutually exclusive (only 2 historical rows use both).
- `nbrDaysPerYear` on the individual `Rate` row is **NOT NULL** — it is required.
  **Never** fall back to `RateStandard.nbrDaysPerYear` for days. Only `dailyRate` may fall back.

```
FTE path:       cost = quantity  × Rate.nbrDaysPerYear × effective_rate
Man-days path:  cost = manDays                         × effective_rate
Direct cost:    cost = quantity  × Rate.dailyRate       (nbrDaysPerYear = 1.0 for licences)
```

---

## Rate Resolution — Always by `initiative.year`

Rates are **always** resolved using the `year` field of the **initiative**, never the current
calendar year. A 2023 initiative always uses 2023 rates, even when consulted in 2026.

**Resolution order:**

1. Look for a `Rate` row matching `(resourceId, initiative.year)` → use its `dailyRate`.
2. If not found, fall back to `RateStandard` matching `(type, initiative.year)` — INTERNAL or
   EXTERNAL only.
3. `DIRECT_COST` has **no** standard fallback. It always requires an individual `Rate` row.

**Never use `new Date().getFullYear()` to select a rate.** Always use `initiative.year`.

---

## FTE / Man-Days Conversion

```
Man Days = quantity × nbrDaysPerYear        (e.g. 0.5 FTE × 200 days = 100 man-days)
FTE %    = manDays  / nbrDaysPerYear × 100  (e.g. 60 days / 200      = 30% FTE)
```

Typical `nbrDaysPerYear` values: **200** internal staff, **220** external, **1.0** direct-cost.

---

## Cost Split — Three Buckets

The `v_allocation_costs` view always produces three non-overlapping columns:

```
internal_cost + external_cost + direct_cost = computed_cost   (guaranteed for every row)
```

Never break this invariant when writing or modifying view SQL.

---

## EOTP Exception Routing

EOTP routing stores **exception-only** EUR amounts. Anything not explicitly routed stays on
the product's default `sapEotpCode` (the "main" bucket — a computed remainder).

**Rules:**
- POST/PATCH to `/api/allocation-entities/[id]/eotp-routing` must **reject** any `eotp` value
  equal to the entity's `sapEotpCode`. The main bucket is never stored — it is always derived.
- Always call `src/lib/eotp-routing-validation.ts` before any write to `eotp_routing`.
- `EotpRouting` rows store EUR amounts (`internalAmount`, `externalAmount`, `directAmount`),
  not percentages.
- Unique constraint: `(allocationEntityId, year, eotp)` — one row per target code per year.

---

## `v_eotp_costs` Structure

- **Non-main rows:** one line per exception routing row (target EOTP ≠ `sapEotpCode`).
- **Main row** (`is_main_eotp = true`): amounts = product-year totals minus non-main routing.
- Derived columns on every row: `cash_out = external_cost + direct_cost`,
  `total_cost = internal_cost + external_cost + direct_cost`.

To recreate only this view: `npm run db:recreate:eotp-costs` (requires `v_allocation_costs`).

